{"title_page": "Sequoia Council", "text_new": ":''(not to be confused with the [[Sequoyah Council]] located in Tennessee and Virginia)''\n{{Infobox WorldScouting\n|name=Sequoia Council #027\n|image=Sequoia Council CSP.png\n|type=council\n|owner=[[Boy Scouts of America]]\n|headquarters=Fresno, California\n|location=\n|country=United States\n|coords=\n|f-date=1919\n|defunct=\n|founders=\n|founder=\n|members=\n|chiefscouttitle=President\n|chiefscout=Richard Egan\n|chiefscouttitle2=Council Commissioner\n|chiefscout2=Richard Schneider\n|chiefscouttitle3=Scout Executive\n|chiefscout3=Mike Marchese\n|website=[https://www.seqbsa.org seqbsa.org]\n}}\nThe '''Sequoia Council''' serves Fresno, Madera, Kings and Tulare Counties in California. Founded in 1919 as the Fresno Council, it changed its name to Sequoia  Council in 1925. In 1992, the  Mount Whitney Area Council (#054) merged into Sequoia.<ref name=\"CSP Book\">{{cite book |last1=Hook|first1=James |last2=Franck |first2=Dave|last3=Austin|first3=Steve |year=1982 |title=An Aid to Collecting Selected Council Shoulder Patches with Valuation |url=http://www.angelfire.com/tx6/patch/cspbook.html}}</ref>\n\n==Organization==\n*San Joaquin District\n*Thunderbird District\n*Riverbend District\n*Live Oak District\n\n==Camps==\n*Camp Chawanakee<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chawanakee.com|title=Camp Chawanakee Online Merit Badge Signups|website=www.chawanakee.com}}</ref>\n*Camp Wortman\n\n==Order of the Arrow==\n*<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tah-heetch.org|title=tah-heetch.org|website=www.tah-heetch.org}}</ref> Tah-Heetch Lodge #195\n\n==See also==\n{{Commons category|Scouting in California}}\n*[[Scouting in California]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{Scouting in the United States}}\n\n[[Category:Local councils of the Boy Scouts of America]]\n[[Category:Organizations based in Fresno, California]]\n[[Category:Youth organizations based in California]]\n[[Category:Non-profit organizations based in California]]\n[[Category:Western Region (Boy Scouts of America)]]\n[[Category:1919 establishments in California]]\n", "text_old": ":''(not to be confused with the [[Sequoyah Council]] located in Tennessee and Virginia)''\n{{Infobox WorldScouting\n|name=Sequoia Council #027\n|image=Sequoia Council CSP.png\n|type=council\n|owner=[[Boy Scouts of America]]\n|headquarters=Fresno, California\n|location=\n|country=United States\n|coords=\n|f-date=1919\n|defunct=\n|founders=\n|founder=\n|members=\n|chiefscouttitle=President\n|chiefscout=Richard Egan\n|chiefscouttitle2=Council Commissioner\n|chiefscout2=Richard Schneider\n|chiefscouttitle3=Scout Executive\n|chiefscout3=John Richers \n|website=[https://www.seqbsa.org seqbsa.org]\n}}\nThe '''Sequoia Council''' serves Fresno, Madera, Kings and Tulare Counties in California. Founded in 1919 as the Fresno Council, it changed its name to Sequoia  Council in 1925. In 1992, the  Mount Whitney Area Council (#054) merged into Sequoia.<ref name=\"CSP Book\">{{cite book |last1=Hook|first1=James |last2=Franck |first2=Dave|last3=Austin|first3=Steve |year=1982 |title=An Aid to Collecting Selected Council Shoulder Patches with Valuation |url=http://www.angelfire.com/tx6/patch/cspbook.html}}</ref>\n\n==Organization==\n*San Joaquin District\n*Thunderbird District\n*Riverbend District\n*Live Oak District\n\n==Camps==\n*Camp Chawanakee<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chawanakee.com|title=Camp Chawanakee Online Merit Badge Signups|website=www.chawanakee.com}}</ref>\n*Camp Wortman\n\n==Order of the Arrow==\n*<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tah-heetch.org|title=tah-heetch.org|website=www.tah-heetch.org}}</ref> Tah-Heetch Lodge #195\n\n==See also==\n{{Commons category|Scouting in California}}\n*[[Scouting in California]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{Scouting in the United States}}\n\n[[Category:Local councils of the Boy Scouts of America]]\n[[Category:Organizations based in Fresno, California]]\n[[Category:Youth organizations based in California]]\n[[Category:Non-profit organizations based in California]]\n[[Category:Western Region (Boy Scouts of America)]]\n[[Category:1919 establishments in California]]\n", "name_user": "Michael R. Marchese", "label": "safe", "comment": "Scout Executive changed positions, John Richers has retired.  Mike Marchese is now serving as Scout Executive.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sequoia_Council"}
{"title_page": "Arthur B. Hancock III", "text_new": "{{About|the grandson (born 1943)|the grandfather (1875-1957)|Arthur B. Hancock}}\n{{short description|American racehorse owner}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name   = Arthur B. Hancock III\n| image_size     = \n| caption  = \n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1943|2|22|mf=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Nashville, Tennessee]], [[United States|U.S.]]\n| death_date  = \n| death_place = \n| occupation     = Thoroughbred racehorse owner/breeder\n| spouse         = Staci\n| parents        = [[Arthur B. Hancock, Jr.]]<br>Waddell Walker \n| children       =<br>'''Son:''' Arthur IV<br>'''Daughters:''' Alex, Hutchi, Kate, Lynn, Walker \n}}\n'''Arthur Boyd Hancock III''' (born February 22, 1943, in [[Nashville, Tennessee]]) is an [[United States|American]] [[owner]] of [[Thoroughbred]] [[horse racing|racehorses]], the owner of [[Stone Farm]], a 2,000 acre (8&nbsp;km\u00b2) [[horse breeding]] operation in [[Paris, Kentucky]], and a composer of [[Bluegrass music]].\n\nHancock is a member of one of the pre-eminent American horse racing families. His grandfather, [[Arthur B. Hancock]] (1875\u20131957), founded [[Claiborne Farm]], his father, [[Arthur B. Hancock, Jr.|Arthur B. \"Bull \" Hancock, Jr.]] (1910\u20131972), expanded the business to where it is considered the most important breeding farm in the U.S. during the 20th century and whose sales and influence also impacted [[Europe]]an racing.<ref>http://www.stonefarm.com/history.html Stone Farm official website with brief Hancock family history</ref>\n \nAfter graduating from [[Vanderbilt University]], Hancock moved to the [[New York City]] area where he worked as an apprentice under future Hall of Fame trainer [[Edward A. Neloy]]. While Hancock's younger brother [[Seth W. Hancock|Seth]] would eventually take over the running of Claiborne Farm, Hancock built Stone Farm into a respected and successful breeding and racing operation which earned the family its first ever win in the [[Kentucky Derby]]. In partnership with one of his longtime clients, [[Manhattan]] real estate broker [[Leone J. Peters]], he bred and raced [[Gato Del Sol]] who won the 1982 Derby.<ref>https://www.nytimes.com/1988/06/07/obituaries/leone-peters-76-dies-real-estate-chairman.html</ref> He and Peters also teamed up to breed [[Risen Star]], winner of the 1988 [[Preakness Stakes|Preakness]] and [[Belmont Stakes]].\n\nThrough [[H-G-W Partners]], Hancock owned and raced 1989 [[Eclipse Award for Horse of the Year|U.S. Horse of the Year]] [[Sunday Silence]] whose wins included the Kentucky Derby, [[Preakness Stakes]], and [[Breeders' Cup Classic]]. Hancock also co-bred the 2000 Kentucky Derby winner [[Fusaichi Pegasus]]. He has also raced in partnership [[Kentucky Oaks]] winner [[Goodbye Halo]] and [[Blue Grass Stakes]] / [[Haskell Invitational Handicap]] winner [[Menifee]].\n\nA member of [[The Jockey Club]], in September 1996, Hancock was elected to the [[board of directors]] of [[Fasig-Tipton|Fasig-Tipton Co.]]\n\nHancock is a devotee of Bluegrass music and has written songs which have been recorded by artists such as [[Grandpa Jones]], [[Willie Nelson]] and [[Ray Price (musician)|Ray Price]].<ref>http://www.stonefarm.com/stoneproductions/liner-notes.html</ref>\n\nHe lives at Stone Farm in Paris, Kentucky with his wife Staci and their six children.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070929101849/http://www.ntra.com/stats_bios.aspx?id=3611 Arthur Hancock III at the NTRA]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hancock, Arthur B., Iii}}\n[[Category:1943 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Vanderbilt University alumni]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Kentucky]]\n[[Category:American racehorse owners and breeders]]\n[[Category:American country songwriters]]\n[[Category:American male songwriters]]\n[[Category:People from Nashville, Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Kentucky]]\n[[Category:Hancock family|Arthur B. Hancock]]\n[[Category:Bluegrass musicians from Kentucky]]\n[[Category:Songwriters from Kentucky]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American racehorse owner}}\n{{About|the grandson (born 1943)|the grandfather (1875-1957)|Arthur B. Hancock}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name   = Arthur B. Hancock III\n| image_size     = \n| caption  = \n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1943|2|22|mf=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Nashville, Tennessee]], [[United States|U.S.]]\n| death_date  = \n| death_place = \n| occupation     = Thoroughbred racehorse owner/breeder\n| spouse         = Staci\n| parents        = [[Arthur B. Hancock, Jr.]]<br>Waddell Walker \n| children       =<br>'''Son:''' Arthur IV<br>'''Daughters:''' Alex, Hutchi, Kate, Lynn, Walker \n}}\n'''Arthur Boyd Hancock III''' (born February 22, 1943, in [[Nashville, Tennessee]]) is an [[United States|American]] [[owner]] of [[Thoroughbred]] [[horse racing|racehorses]], the owner of [[Stone Farm]], a 2,000 acre (8&nbsp;km\u00b2) [[horse breeding]] operation in [[Paris, Kentucky]], and a composer of [[Bluegrass music]].\n\nHancock is a member of one of the pre-eminent American horse racing families. His grandfather, [[Arthur B. Hancock]] (1875\u20131957), founded [[Claiborne Farm]], his father, [[Arthur B. Hancock, Jr.|Arthur B. \"Bull \" Hancock, Jr.]] (1910\u20131972), expanded the business to where it is considered the most important breeding farm in the U.S. during the 20th century and whose sales and influence also impacted [[Europe]]an racing.<ref>http://www.stonefarm.com/history.html Stone Farm official website with brief Hancock family history</ref>\n \nAfter graduating from [[Vanderbilt University]], Hancock moved to the [[New York City]] area where he worked as an apprentice under future Hall of Fame trainer [[Edward A. Neloy]]. While Hancock's younger brother [[Seth W. Hancock|Seth]] would eventually take over the running of Claiborne Farm, Hancock built Stone Farm into a respected and successful breeding and racing operation which earned the family its first ever win in the [[Kentucky Derby]]. In partnership with one of his longtime clients, [[Manhattan]] real estate broker [[Leone J. Peters]], he bred and raced [[Gato Del Sol]] who won the 1982 Derby.<ref>https://www.nytimes.com/1988/06/07/obituaries/leone-peters-76-dies-real-estate-chairman.html</ref> He and Peters also teamed up to breed [[Risen Star]], winner of the 1988 [[Preakness Stakes|Preakness]] and [[Belmont Stakes]].\n\nThrough [[H-G-W Partners]], Hancock owned and raced 1989 [[Eclipse Award for Horse of the Year|U.S. Horse of the Year]] [[Sunday Silence]] whose wins included the Kentucky Derby, [[Preakness Stakes]], and [[Breeders' Cup Classic]]. Hancock also co-bred the 2000 Kentucky Derby winner [[Fusaichi Pegasus]]. He has also raced in partnership [[Kentucky Oaks]] winner [[Goodbye Halo]] and [[Blue Grass Stakes]] / [[Haskell Invitational Handicap]] winner [[Menifee]].\n\nA member of [[The Jockey Club]], in September 1996, Hancock was elected to the [[board of directors]] of [[Fasig-Tipton|Fasig-Tipton Co.]]\n\nHancock is a devotee of Bluegrass music and has written songs which have been recorded by artists such as [[Grandpa Jones]], [[Willie Nelson]] and [[Ray Price (musician)|Ray Price]].<ref>http://www.stonefarm.com/stoneproductions/liner-notes.html</ref>\n\nHe lives at Stone Farm in Paris, Kentucky with his wife Staci and their six children.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070929101849/http://www.ntra.com/stats_bios.aspx?id=3611 Arthur Hancock III at the NTRA]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hancock, Arthur B., Iii}}\n[[Category:1943 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Vanderbilt University alumni]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Kentucky]]\n[[Category:American racehorse owners and breeders]]\n[[Category:American country songwriters]]\n[[Category:American male songwriters]]\n[[Category:People from Nashville, Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Kentucky]]\n[[Category:Hancock family|Arthur B. Hancock]]\n[[Category:Bluegrass musicians from Kentucky]]\n[[Category:Songwriters from Kentucky]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arthur_B._Hancock_III"}
{"title_page": "Guangzhou R&F F.C.", "text_new": "{{Infobox football club\n| clubname    = Guangzhou R&F<br>Gu\u01cengzh\u014du F\u00f9l\u00ec<br>\u5e7f\u5dde\u5bcc\u529b\n| image       = Guangzhou R&F FC logo.svg\n| image_size  = 180px\n| fullname    = Guangzhou R&F Football Club<br />\u5e7f\u5dde\u5bcc\u529b\u8db3\u7403\u4ff1\u4e50\u90e8\n| nickname    = Blue Lions<ref>{{cite web|last1=Murphy|first1=Ronan|title=Is this the weirdest Chinese Super League transfer yet?|url=http://www.goal.com/en-au/news/4019/transfer-zone/2017/01/05/31153782/is-this-the-weirdest-chinese-super-league-transfer-yet|publisher=goal.com|accessdate=5 January 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170105175834/http://www.goal.com/en-au/news/4019/transfer-zone/2017/01/05/31153782/is-this-the-weirdest-chinese-super-league-transfer-yet|archivedate=5 January 2017}}</ref>\n| founded     = {{Start date and age|1986}}, as Shenyang Football Team\n| ground      = [[Yuexiushan Stadium]],<br />[[Guangzhou]], [[Guangdong]], China\n| capacity    = 18,000<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefootballstadiums.com/yuexiushan-stadium|title=Yuexiushan Stadium \u2013 stadion \u2013 The Football Stadiums.com \u2013 Database of football stadiums|first=Jiri Vojkovsky|last=www.TheFootballStadiums.com|website=www.thefootballstadiums.com|accessdate=5 May 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170817205652/http://www.thefootballstadiums.com/yuexiushan-stadium|archivedate=17 August 2017}}</ref>\n| owner       = [[R&F Properties]]\n| chairman    = Zhang Li\n| manager     = [[Giovanni van Bronckhorst]]<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.dutchnews.nl/news/2020/01/giovanni-van-bronckhorst-is-moving-to-china-to-take-over-the-helm-at-guangzhou/|title=Giovanni van Bronckhorst is moving to China to take over the helm at Guangzhou|website=Dutchnews.nl|accessdate=3 January 2020}}</ref>\n| league      = [[Chinese Super League]]\n| season      = [[2020 Chinese Super League|2020]]\n| position    = Super League\n| website     = http://www.gzrffc.com.cn\n| current     = 2020 Guangzhou R&F F.C. season\n| pattern_la1 = _guangzhour&f18h\n| pattern_b1  = _guangzhour&f18h\n| pattern_ra1 = _guangzhour&f18h\n| pattern_sh1 = _guangzhour&f18h\n| pattern_so1 = _guangzhour&f18h\n| leftarm1    = FFFFFF\n| body1       = FFFFFF\n| rightarm1   = FFFFFF\n| shorts1     = FFFFFF\n| socks1      = FFFFFF\n| pattern_la2 = _guangzhour&f16a\n| pattern_b2  = _guangzhour&f18a\n| pattern_ra2 = _guangzhour&f18a\n| pattern_sh2 = _guangzhour&f18a\n| pattern_so2 = _guangzhour&f19a\n| leftarm2    = 0000FF\n| body2       = 0000FF\n| rightarm2   = 0000FF\n| shorts2     = 0000FF\n| socks2      = 0000FF\n}}\n{{Infobox Chinese\n|s=\u5e7f\u5dde\u5bcc\u529b\n|t=\u5ee3\u5dde\u5bcc\u529b\n|tp=Gu\u01cengjhou F\u00f9l\u00ec\n|p=Gu\u01cengzh\u014du F\u00f9l\u00ec\n|w=Kuang<sup>3</sup>chou<sup>1</sup> Fu<sup>4</sup>li<sup>4</sup>\n|mi={{IPAc-cmn|g|wang|3|-|zh|ou|1|-|f|u|4|-|l|i|4|}}\n|myr=Gw\u01cengj\u014du F\u00f9l\u00ec\n|gr=Goangjou Fuhlih\n|bpmf={{nowrap|\u310d\u3128\u3124\u02c7 \u3113\u3121 \u3108\u3128\u02cb \u310c\u3127\u02cb}}\n|mps=Gu\u01ceng-j\u014du F\u00f9-l\u00ec\n|zh-dungan=\n|y=Gw\u00f3ngz\u0101u Fulihk <br> Gwong<sup>2</sup>zau<sup>1</sup> Fu<sup>3</sup>lik<sup>6</sup>\n|j=Gwong2zau1 Fu3lihk6\n|gd=guong<sup>2</sup> zeo<sup>1</sup> fu<sup>3</sup> lig<sup>6</sup>\n|hk=Kwong Tsau Fu Lik <br> Kwong Tsau Foo Lik\n|ci={{IPAc-yue|gw|ong|2|-|z|au|1|-|f|u|3|-|l|ik|6}}\n| order = st\n}}\n\n'''Guangzhou R&F Football Club''' is a professional [[Association football|football]] club that plays in the [[Chinese Super League]] under licence from the [[Chinese Football Association]] (CFA). The team is based in [[Guangzhou]], [[Guangdong]], and their home stadium is the [[Yuexiushan Stadium]] which has a seating capacity of 18,000. They are owned by the Chinese property developers [[R&F Properties]] who took charge in June 2011. The club's English name R&F is short for \"Rich\" (\u5bcc) and \"Force\" (\u529b).\n\nThe club was founded in 1986 in [[Shenyang]] as Shenyang Football Team. They played at the 55,000-seat [[Wulihe Stadium]] (\u4e94\u91cc\u6cb3\u4f53\u80b2\u573a), until they moved to Changsha in 2007 to reside in the [[Helong Sports Center Stadium|Helong Stadium]].  American sportswear and sports equipment company MAZAMBA took over the club in 2010, and relocated the club to [[Shenzhen]] in February 2011. Their ownership was brief, and by June 2011 Chinese property developers Guangzhou R&F gained ownership of the club and moved them to Guangzhou. The club had their most successful season in 2014 as they finished third in the league and qualified for the [[2015 AFC Champions League]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://int.soccerway.com/national/china-pr/csl/2014/regular-season/r23926/|title=Summary&nbsp;\u2013 CSL&nbsp;\u2013 China PR&nbsp;\u2013 Results, fixtures, tables and news&nbsp;\u2013 Soccerway|website=uk.soccerway.com|access-date=2016-03-12|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151229010530/http://int.soccerway.com/national/china-pr/csl/2014/regular-season/r23926/|archivedate=2015-12-29}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nThe club was founded in 1986 by the local [[Shenyang]] government sports body to take part in the Chinese football league system. The club was named \"Shenyang\" (\u6c88\u9633). The team started at the bottom of the league system by playing in the second division. They were promoted to the [[Chinese Jia-A League 1988|1988 Chinese Jia-A League]] quickly after the league expanded and [[Liaoning Whowin F.C.|Liaoning FC]] was ineligible to field their reserve team in the same division. The club was relegated after only one season.<ref>[http://www.rsssf.com/tablesc/chinahist.html#88 China League History<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140607124048/http://www.rsssf.com/tablesc/chinahist.html |date=2014-06-07 }} at rsssf.com. 22 Oct 2009. Retrieved 2013-06-04.</ref> With the following campaigns the club mostly remained within the second tier, except for a short foray in the [[Chinese Jia-A League 1992|1992 Chinese Jia-A League campaign]]; however, again they were relegated after only one season.\n\nBy the 1994 league season the entire Chinese football league system had become professional. The team were allowed to gather sponsorship and rename themselves '''Shenyang Liuyao''' (\u6c88\u9633\u4e1c\u5317\u516d\u836f), and were allowed to join the top tier due to their 1992 membership.<ref name=\"China 1994\">[http://www.rsssf.com/tablesc/china94.html China League 1994<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140727150541/http://www.rsssf.com/tablesc/china94.html |date=2014-07-27 }} at rsssf.com. 19 Jun 2003. Retrieved 2013-06-04.</ref> When the team were relegated again at the end of the season they rename themselves '''Shenyang Huayang''' (\u6c88\u9633\u534e\u9633) and then '''Shenyang Sealion''' (\u6c88\u9633\u6d77\u72ee) in 1996. Again the club won promotion to the top tier; however, unlike before they were able to avoid relegation. This was to be the beginning of the club's establishment within the league, though the team benefitted from several seasons where there was no relegation while the league expanded. In 2001 the club was taken over by Ginde Plastic Pipe Industry Group, a subsidiary of the Hongyuan Group and changed its name to '''Shenyang Ginde''' (\u6c88\u9633\u91d1\u5fb7). In 2007 the club's homeground [[Wulihe Stadium]] (\u4e94\u91cc\u6cb3\u4f53\u80b2\u573a) was demolished. While it was expected that the club move to another stadium within Shenyang, especially the [[Shenyang Olympic Sports Center Stadium]], a deal did not go through and the club moved to [[Changsha]] in [[Hunan]] and changed their name to '''Changsha Ginde''' (\u957f\u6c99\u91d1\u5fb7).\n\nAfter Changsha Ginde were relegated to League One at the end of the 2010 league season, the club was purchased by MAZAMBA and moved into the [[Shenzhen Stadium]] in the city of [[Shenzhen]], [[Guangdong]] in February 2011. To represent this change the owners changed the club's name to '''Shenzhen Phoenix''' and changed the home kit from sky blue to green.<ref name=\"Shenzhen Phoenix\">[http://sports.sohu.com/20110227/n279546061.shtml \u957f\u6c99\u91d1\u5fb7\u5c06\u66f4\u540d\u843d\u6237\u6df1\u5733 \u5c06\u52a0\u7d27\u786e\u5b9a\u4e3b\u5e05\u5185\u5916\u63f4] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716103123/http://sports.sohu.com/20110227/n279546061.shtml |date=2011-07-16 }} at sports.sohu.com. 2011-02-27. Retrieved 2013-06-04. {{in lang|zh}}</ref> By May 2011 the club was exposed as having serious financial problems and were struggling to pay their players and their hotel accommodation.<ref>[http://sports.sina.com.cn/b/2011-05-23/15035589088.shtml \u4e2d\u7532\u6df1\u5733\u961f\u7a77\u56f0\u8bf7\u7403\u5458\u5bb6\u5c5e\u7ed3\u623f\u8d39 \u96be\u4ee5\u7ef4\u6301\u6216\u9000\u8d5b] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110526094049/http://sports.sina.com.cn/b/2011-05-23/15035589088.shtml |date=2011-05-26 }} at sports.sina.com.cn. 2011-05-23. Retrieved 2013-06-04. {{in lang|zh}}</ref>\n\n=== History as Guangzhou R&F ===\nIn serious doubt of completing the 2011 season, Shenzhen Phoenix was put up for sale. The club was bought by Chinese property developers [[Guangzhou R&F F.C.|Guangzhou R&F]] who moved the club to the [[Yuexiushan Stadium]] in [[Guangzhou]] and changed the club's colours back to blue.<ref name=\"Guangzhou R&F\">[http://sports.sina.com.cn/b/2011-06-25/08575632297.shtml \u5bcc\u529b\u5730\u4ea7\u4f4e\u8c03\u63a5\u624b\u6df1\u5733\u51e4\u51f0 \u671b\u5b66\u6052\u5927\u6a21\u5f0f\u5165\u4e3b\u8db3\u7403] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121015190141/http://sports.sina.com.cn/b/2011-06-25/08575632297.shtml |date=2012-10-15 }} at sports.sina.com.cn. 2011-06-25. Retrieved 2013-06-04. {{in lang|zh}}</ref> Under the new ownership results significantly improved and the club gained promotion back into the top tier at the end of the [[2011 China League One]] season. The team finished the league in seventh, and the club's owners decided to commit their long-term future to the club by establishing a football school in [[Meizhou]].<ref>[http://wildeastfootball.net/2013/05/guangzhou-rf-and-chelsea-fc-open-football-school/ Guangzhou R&F and Chelsea FC open football school] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402154136/http://wildeastfootball.net/2013/05/guangzhou-rf-and-chelsea-fc-open-football-school/ |date=2015-04-02 }} at wildeastfootball.net. May 16, 2013. Retrieved 2013-06-04.</ref> The start of the [[2013 Chinese Super League]] season, however, the club struggled in the league and the manager [[S\u00e9rgio Farias]] was fired. Former England manager [[Sven-G\u00f6ran Eriksson]] was appointed to replace him on June 4, 2013, and given a 19-month contract.<ref>[http://www.thesackrace.com/news/4th-june-2013/sven-goran-eriksson-takes-charge-of-guangzhou-rf Sven Goran Eriksson takes charge of Guangzhou R&F] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131101020458/http://www.thesackrace.com/news/4th-june-2013/sven-goran-eriksson-takes-charge-of-guangzhou-rf |date=2013-11-01 }} at thesackrace.com. 4th-june-2013. Retrieved 2013-06-04.</ref> Eriksson's first full season would see the club finish third, its highest league finish, and qualify for the [[AFC Champions League|Asian Champions League]] for the first time. Moroccan striker [[Abderrazak Hamdallah|Abderazzak Hamdallah]] was a key player for the team, scoring 22 times in 22 appearances. However, manager Eriksson left at the end of his contract and moved to [[Shanghai SIPG F.C.|Shanghai SIPG]] who had finished fifth that year.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nOn January 2, 2015, the club announced that [[Cosmin Contra]] would be their new manager.<ref>{{cite news|title=\u5bcc\u529b\u5ba3\u5e03\u5b54\u7279\u62c9\u4e0b\u5468\u4e00\u6b63\u5f0f\u63a5\u624b \u5218\u6bbf\u5ea7\u786e\u5b9a\u52a0\u76df|url=http://sports.163.com/15/0102/08/AEUJTBN100051C89.html#from=relevant#xwwzy_35_bottomnewskwd|agency=\u7f51\u6613\u65b0\u95fb|publisher=\u5e7f\u5dde\u65e5\u62a5|date=4 January 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150104152551/http://sports.163.com/15/0102/08/AEUJTBN100051C89.html#from=relevant|archivedate=4 January 2015}}</ref> Contra coached the club in their maiden appearance in the Asian Champions League, coming through the preliminary stages against [[Warriors FC]] and [[Central Coast Mariners FC|Central Coast Mariners]] to earn a place in the group stage.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2015/feb/18/central-coast-mariners-guangzhou-rf-report|title=Central Coast fail to qualify for Asian Champions League after playoff defeat|last=Press|first=Australian Associated|date=2015-02-17|newspaper=The Guardian|issn=0261-3077|access-date=2016-03-12|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160313044719/http://www.theguardian.com/football/2015/feb/18/central-coast-mariners-guangzhou-rf-report|archivedate=2016-03-13}}</ref> However, despite an away victory over Gamba Osaka, Guangzhou R&F were eliminated at the group stage.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.espnfc.co.uk/gamba-osaka/story/2316657/asian-champions-league-wrap-guangzhou-randf-stun-gamba-osaka|title=Guangzhou R&F stun Gamba Osaka in Asian Champions League opener|website=ESPNFC.com|access-date=2016-03-12|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160313033514/http://www.espnfc.co.uk/gamba-osaka/story/2316657/asian-champions-league-wrap-guangzhou-randf-stun-gamba-osaka|archivedate=2016-03-13}}</ref> The club's league form was also poor and Contra was sacked on July 22. [[Li Bing (footballer)|Li Bing]] was installed as caretaker manager.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gzrffc.com.cn/index.php?m=Article&a=show&id=834|title=\u901a \u544a-\u516c\u544a|website=www.gzrffc.com.cn|access-date=2016-03-12|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160313050218/http://www.gzrffc.com.cn/index.php?m=Article&a=show&id=834|archivedate=2016-03-13}}</ref> There were more changes as Korean defensive midfielder [[Park Jong-woo]] and the injured and unsettled Hamdallah also left the club mid-season. Hamdallah only scored three goals in 2015, making him the club's all-time leading foreign scorer at the time with 25, one ahead of [[Yakubu (footballer)|Yakubu]]. The disruption continued as R&F were forced to play some of their home matches at Guangzhou's [[Guangzhou Higher Education Mega Center Central Stadium|University City Stadium]] whilst Yuexiushan was being refurbished, just as in 2012.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wildeastfootball.net/2013/11/guangzhou-rf-2013-season-review-work-in-progress/|title=Guangzhou R&F 2013 Season Review: Work in progress : Wild East Football|website=wildeastfootball.net|access-date=2016-08-27|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160804142004/http://wildeastfootball.net/2013/11/guangzhou-rf-2013-season-review-work-in-progress/|archivedate=2016-08-04}}</ref> \n\n==== The Dragan Stojkovic era ====\nGuangzhou R&F announced [[Dragan Stojkovi\u0107]] as their new manager on 24 August and handed the former Yugoslav international a contract to the end of the 2017 season.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gzrffc.com.cn/index.php?m=Article&a=show&id=854|title=\u5173\u4e8e\u8058\u8bf7\u5fb7\u62c9\u7518\u00b7\u65af\u6258\u4f0a\u79d1\u7ef4\u5947\u62c5\u4efb\u5e7f\u5dde\u5bcc\u529b\u8db3\u7403\u4ff1\u4e50\u90e8\u4e3b\u6559\u7ec3\u7684\u516c\u544a-\u516c\u544a|website=www.gzrffc.com.cn|access-date=2016-03-12|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160313045606/http://www.gzrffc.com.cn/index.php?m=Article&a=show&id=854|archivedate=2016-03-13}}</ref> Stojkovic preserved R&F's top flight status as they finished 14th out of 16 teams in 2015.\n\nIn July 2016, R&F signed Israeli international [[Eran Zahavi]] from [[Maccabi Tel Aviv F.C.]] Whilst home stadium Yuexiushan was being refurbished, R&F played their opening home games in 2017 at the [[Guangdong Provincial People's Stadium]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wildeastfootball.net/2017/03/from-the-qing-dynasty-to-collapsing-roofs-and-the-csl-a-history-of-guangzhou-rfs-temporary-home/|title=From the Qing dynasty, to collapsing roofs and the CSL: a history of Guangzhou R&F's temporary home \u2013 Wild East Football|website=wildeastfootball.net|access-date=2017-11-05|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170521150448/https://wildeastfootball.net/2017/03/from-the-qing-dynasty-to-collapsing-roofs-and-the-csl-a-history-of-guangzhou-rfs-temporary-home/|archivedate=2017-05-21}}</ref> Stojkovic's attacking style of play and Zahavi's goals led R&F to finish fifth in the CSL in 2017. There was double disappointment on the final day of the season however as the club fell just short of qualifying for the ACL and Zahavi missed out on breaking the single season CSL scoring record by just one goal. However, his 27 goals earned him the 2017 golden boot.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://sports.sina.com.cn/china/j/2017-11-04/doc-ifynmzrs7047612.shtml|title=\u624e\u7403\u738b27\u7403\u65a9\u91d1\u9774\u6709\u9057\u61be \u79bb\u57c3\u795e\u7eaa\u5f55\u5c31\u5dee1\u4e2a\u5355\u5200|website=sports.sina.com.cn|access-date=2017-11-05|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107023123/http://sports.sina.com.cn/china/j/2017-11-04/doc-ifynmzrs7047612.shtml|archivedate=2017-11-07}}</ref> Guangzhou R&F reached the semi-finals of the CFA Cup in 2018 but had a disappointing CSL campaign as they finished 10th.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.soccerway.com/national/china-pr/csl/2018/regular-season/r44946/|title=CSL 2018 Summary|access-date=2018-12-16}}</ref>\n\nGuangzhou R&F finished 12th in the CSL in [[2019 Chinese Super League|2019]]. In attack, Zahavi's 29 goals set a new single season scoring record<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/israels-zahavi-sets-single-season-scoring-record-in-chinese-soccer/|title=Israel\u2019s Zahavi sets single season scoring record for Chinese soccer|last=staff|first=T. O. I.|website=www.timesofisrael.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-11}}</ref> but the team had the worst defensive record in the league, conceding 72 goals in 30 games.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wildeastfootball.net/2020/01/stojkovic-departs-van-bronckhorst-arrives/|title=Stojkovi\u0107 departs, van Bronckhorst arrives at Guangzhou R&F|last=Ross|first=Donald|date=2020-01-04|website=Wild East Football|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-01-11}}</ref> After spending over four seasons at the club - making him Guangzhou R&F's longest ever serving manager - Stojkovic left the club in January 2020.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-soccer-china-idUKKBN1Z20JC|title=Stojkovic leaves Guangzhou by mutual consent|date=2020-01-03|work=Reuters|access-date=2020-01-11|language=en}}</ref>\n\n[[Giovanni van Bronckhorst]] was announced as Guangzhou R&F's new manager on 4 January 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2020-01/04/c_138678033.htm|title=Van Bronckhorst appointed Guangzhou R&F head coach - Xinhua {{!}} English.news.cn|website=www.xinhuanet.com|access-date=2020-01-11}}</ref>\n\n== Name history ==\n*1986\u20131993: '''Shenyang''' (\u6c88\u9633)\n*1994: '''Shenyang Liuyao''' (\u6c88\u9633\u4e1c\u5317\u516d\u836f)<ref name=\"China 1994\"/>\n*1995: '''Shenyang Huayang''' (\u6c88\u9633\u534e\u9633)\n*1996\u20132001: '''Shenyang Sealion''' (\u6c88\u9633\u6d77\u72ee)\n*2001\u20132006: '''Shenyang Ginde''' (\u6c88\u9633\u91d1\u5fb7)\n*2007\u20132010: '''Changsha Ginde''' (\u957f\u6c99\u91d1\u5fb7)\n*2011\uff1a'''Shenzhen Phoenix''' (\u6df1\u5733\u51e4\u51f0)<ref name=\"Shenzhen Phoenix\"/>\n*2011\u2013\uff1a'''Guangzhou R&F''' (\u5e7f\u5dde\u5bcc\u529b)<ref name=\"Guangzhou R&F\"/>\n\n== Rivalries ==\n{{main|Guangzhou Derbies}}\nThe club took part in the Liaoning Derby, which was a regional fixture contested against [[Dalian Shide F.C.|Dalian Football Club]] and [[Liaoning Whowin F.C.|Liaoning FC]] while the club was located in Shenyang.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wildeastfootball.net/2011/06/a-guide-to-football-in-shenyang/|title=A Guide to Football in Shenyang|publisher=wildeastfootball.net|date=2011-06-15|accessdate=2015-09-15|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150912172529/http://wildeastfootball.net/2011/06/a-guide-to-football-in-shenyang/|archivedate=2015-09-12}}</ref> The tie against Liaoning FC was the more intimate affair because the clubs shared the Shenyang People's Stadium in the [[Chinese Jia-A League 1994|1994 league season]] compared to the Dalian fixture, which historically saw few meaningful clashes. At the end of the 2006 league season the club left this derby when they moved out of Shenyang.\n\nWhen the club moved to [[Guangzhou]] they soon formed a rivalry with [[Guangzhou Evergrande Taobao F.C.|Guangzhou Evergrande]], which is often referred to as the Canton derby.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wildeastfootball.net/2014/09/yuexiushan-news-canton-derby/|title=Yuexiushan News: Canton Derby|publisher=wildeastfootball.net|date=2014-09-26|accessdate=2015-09-15|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150909233219/http://wildeastfootball.net/2014/09/yuexiushan-news-canton-derby/|archivedate=2015-09-09}}</ref> The first derby was played at [[Yuexiushan Stadium]] in a league match on March 16, 2012 and Guangzhou R&F won 2\u20130 at home against the reigning league champions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.sohu.com/20120316/n338005769.shtml|title=\u5f20\u70c1\u5f20\u8fdc\u8054\u8882\u53d1\u5a01 \u5bcc\u529b\u518d\u7206\u51b72\u20130\u6052\u5927|publisher=sports.sohu.com|date=2012-03-16|accessdate=2015-09-15|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151119074245/http://sports.sohu.com/20120316/n338005769.shtml|archivedate=2015-11-19}}</ref> The venue was significant because it had been Guangzhou Evergrande's home ground. However, the two club owners, Zhang Li and [[Xu Jiayin]], did not view the derby with hostility and on the return fixture, which R&F won 1\u20130. They were seen enjoying a meal together instead of watching the game.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wildeastfootball.net/2012/07/drunken-club-owners-miss-guangzhou-derby/|title=Drunken Club Owners Miss Guangzhou Derby|publisher=wildeastfootball.net|date=2012-07-21|accessdate=2015-09-15|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150926232111/http://wildeastfootball.net/2012/07/drunken-club-owners-miss-guangzhou-derby/|archivedate=2015-09-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://wildeastfootball.net/2012/07/yak-attack-nicks-guangzhou-derby-for-rf/|title=Yak Attack Nicks Guangzhou Derby for R&F : Wild East Football|website=wildeastfootball.net|access-date=2016-03-12|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160221032120/http://wildeastfootball.net/2012/07/yak-attack-nicks-guangzhou-derby-for-rf/|archivedate=2016-02-21}}</ref>\n\n== Current squad ==\n\n=== First team ===\n''As of 1 August 2019''<ref>[http://sports.sina.com.cn/china/j/2019-03-02/doc-ihsxncvf9183907.shtml 2019\u8d5b\u5b63\u5e7f\u5dde\u5bcc\u529b\u5927\u540d\u5355:\u767b\u8d1d\u83b1+\u624e\u54c8\u7ef4\u661f\u5149\u8000\u773c] sina.com 2019-03-01 Retrieved 2019-03-01</ref>\n\n{{Fs start}}\n{{Fs player|no= 1|nat=CHN|name=[[Cheng Yuelei]]|pos=GK}}\n{{Fs player|no= 3|nat=SER|name=[[Du\u0161ko To\u0161i\u0107]]|pos=DF}}\n{{Fs player|no= 4|nat=CHN|name=[[Zhang Gong]]|pos=MF}}\n{{Fs player|no= 6|nat=CHN|name=[[Fan Yunlong]]|pos=MF}}\n{{Fs player|no= 7|nat=ISR|name=[[Eran Zahavi]]|pos=FW}}\n{{Fs player|no= 8|nat=BEL|name=[[Mousa Demb\u00e9l\u00e9 (Belgian footballer)|Mousa Demb\u00e9l\u00e9]]|pos=MF}}\n{{Fs player|no= 9|nat=CHN|name=[[Gui Hong]]|pos=FW}}\n{{Fs player|no=10|nat=ISR|name=[[Dia Saba]]|pos=FW}}\n{{Fs player|no=11|nat=BRA|name=[[Renato Ribeiro Calixto|Renatinho]]|pos=MF}}\n{{Fs player|no=13|nat=CHN|nam